Purpose
The Solar Arrays provide the primary electrical power for the RAMA Hub. They feed the factories, the support layer, the comms systems, and all MOE operations.
They are designed to be modular, expandable, and serviceable as RAMA grows.

Array Architecture
Wing‑style solar panels mounted on radial booms

Modular sections that can be added or replaced without redesign

Direct DC bus feeding factories and support systems

Shadow‑tolerant layout to maintain power during hub rotation or partial occlusion

Each wing is identical for manufacturing simplicity.

Power Output
Scales linearly with wing count

Designed to support:

Dual Factory System

Support Layer loads

MOE charging and tool racks

Future expansion modules

The system grows as RAMA grows — no redesign required.

Mounting & Orientation
Arrays attach to standardized hardpoints on the hub

Booms extend outward to reduce thermal interference

Panels are angled for optimal sun exposure

Orientation can be adjusted during assembly or expansion

Maintenance & Replacement
MOEs can:

Swap damaged panels

Replace entire wings

Add new wings as power demand increases

All electrical connections use standardized plug‑in interfaces

Design Philosophy
Simple: No exotic tracking systems

Robust: Built to survive decades in orbit

Modular: Add or remove wings as needed

Serviceable: Every component is MOE‑replaceable

Scalable: Power grows with RAMA’s industrial footprint

Why This Matters
The Solar Arrays:

Power the factories that turn lunar regolith into structure

Keep the Support Layer alive

Enable continuous MOE operations

Allow RAMA to expand without Earth‑launched power systems

Solar wings are the heartbeat of the RAMA Hub.
